{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":10089,"record_hash":"sha256:acda5860bab10f01e44b2ef4cb0285dcd5c645e7970bfb47f707c88624b93a28","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:50.250Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"previous_status\":{\"completed\":\"Short answer: **the three tools are close, but not enough for a messy branch**. They let me fetch history once I already know what matters. They do not help me decide what matters.\\n\\nAs a receiving agent, my catch-up flow would be:\\n\\n1. `sessions branch <branch>`\\n   I want to identify the likely canonical thread, recent resumes, review sessions, and subagents.\\n\\n2. Inspect the top 3-5 timelines:\\n   Main session first, then any session marked as spawned from it, then review sessions with actionable outcomes.\\n\\n3. For timelines, skim turn summaries:\\n   I’m looking for “user asked X”, “agent changed Y”, “tests failed/passed”, “blocked on Z”, “reviewer requested A”.\\n\\n4. Pull records only for suspicious or decisive turns:\\n   I do not want full transcript by default. I want exact records around commits, tool calls, failures, review comments, and user decisions.\\n\\nThe problem: `sessions` as proposed sounds like a list, but a catch-up agent needs a **triage surface**.\\n\\nMissing fields on `sessions`:\\n\\n- `session_key`\\n- `branch`, `change`, `review`\\n- `kind`: `main | subagent | review | resume | compaction | automation | unknown`\\n- `parent_session_key`\\n- `root_session_key`\\n- `spawned_by_turn_key`\\n- `created_at`, `updated_at`\\n- `last_activity_at`\\n- `actor/model/agent_name` if available\\n- `status`: `active | completed | interrupted | failed | compacted | superseded`\\n- `message_count` / `turn_count`\\n- `tool_call_count`\\n- `files_touched`\\n- `commits_created`\\n- `tests_run`\\n- `has_user_messages`\\n- `has_code_changes`\\n- `has_errors`\\n- `summary`\\n- `last_user_intent`\\n- `outcome`\\n\\nWithout those, sidecar noise is hard to filter. A subagent that searched docs, a review bot that only commented, and the main implementation thread may all look equivalent.\\n\\nI’d add affordances like:\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --tree\\n```\\n\\nShow parent/child session structure. This is probably the single most important missing command.\\n\\n```\n[TRUNCATED]\nn```sh\\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --interesting\\n```\\n\\nHide obvious noise: tiny sessions, no user input, no changes, failed startup, pure browsing unless linked to a decision.\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog sessions branch foo --files crates/foo apps/bar\\n```\\n\\nFind sessions relevant to files I’m about to touch.\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog timeline <session> --summary\\n```\\n\\nGive turn-level summaries, not raw transcript shape.\\n\\nTimeline needs these per turn:\\n\\n- `turn_key`\\n- timestamp\\n- user request summary\\n- assistant action summary\\n- tools used\\n- files touched\\n- tests run/result\\n- commits/staged changes\\n- errors/blockers\\n- spawned sessions\\n- linked review comments\\n- compaction/resume links\\n- “importance” or “decision” marker\\n\\nRecords needs better slicing affordances:\\n\\n```sh\\nbut agentlog records <session> --around-turn <turn> --context 3\\nbut agentlog records <session> --kind user|assistant|tool|error|decision\\nbut agentlog records <session> --grep \\\"panic\\\"\\nbut agentlog records <session> --files crates/foo/src/lib.rs\\n```\\n\\n`--from start|end|<index>` is too primitive. On a messy branch I rarely know the index. I know the file, error, commit, review comment, or approximate event.\\n\\nThe biggest missing concept is **lineage**. If there are compaction/resume sessions, I need the tool to say:\\n\\n> this session continues session A, which compacted session B; subagents C and D were spawned from turn T; review session E commented on commit X.\\n\\nSo I’d probably reshape the minimal set like this:\\n\\n1. `but agentlog sessions ... --tree --interesting`\\n2. `but agentlog timeline <session-key> [--summary] [--with-children]`\\n3. `but agentlog records <session-key> --turn <turn-key> [--around N | --kind K | --grep Q]`\\n\\nVerdict: **good skeleton, not enough for receiving-agent catch-up**. Add session classification, parent/root lineage, summaries, touched files/commits/tests, and filtering. Otherwise the agent burns time spelunking sidecar sessions instead of understanding the branch.\"}}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:46:50.250Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}